I"å<p>This website should be maintained collectively by the members of the group. 
Please remember that the <a href="/manual/coc">Code of Conduct</a> applies to content on 
the website, including blog posts and comments.</p>

<h2 id="set-up">Set Up</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Install the build dependencies for the website. These include ruby, jekyll, 
and jekyll-scholar. Get started <a href="https://jekyllrb.com/docs/installation/">here.</a>.</li>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/arfc/arfc.github.io#fork-destination-box">Fork</a> the website repository.</li>
  <li>Clone your fork. If you have <a href="https://help.github.com/articles/generating-an-ssh-key/">your ssh keys set up</a> 
and your username is USERNAME, the command is <code class="highlighter-rouge">git clone 
git@github.com:USERNAME/arfc.github.io</code></li>
  <li>Add the group fork as a remote. <code class="highlighter-rouge">cd arfc.github.io &amp;&amp; git remote add 
upstream git@github.com:arfc/arfc.github.io</code></li>
</ol>

<p>Now, youâ€™re ready to make changes to the website. There are a few types of 
changes that are common:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Edits to the text</li>
  <li>Adding yourself to the people page</li>
  <li>Creating a blog post</li>
</ul>

<p>See below for directions on all of these.</p>

<h2 id="add-yourself">Add Yourself</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Once you have done the set up steps, enter the source branch of the repository. <code class="highlighter-rouge">git checkout source</code></li>
  <li>Add your photo to the repository (in img/people). If your name is Jane Doe, call it <code class="highlighter-rouge">doej.png</code>.</li>
  <li>Donâ€™t forget to git add and git commit the photo <code class="highlighter-rouge">git add img/people/doej.png</code> and <code class="highlighter-rouge">git commit -am "adds a photo of Jane Doe"</code></li>
  <li>Open the file <code class="highlighter-rouge">_data/people.yml</code> and add your details.</li>
  <li>Close the file and commit your changes (<code class="highlighter-rouge">git commit -am "added Jane Doe details to people data"</code>)</li>
  <li>Check whether your changes succeeded by typing <code class="highlighter-rouge">jekyll serve</code> from the top 
level directory of the website repository. Then, open a browser to 
<code class="highlighter-rouge">localhost:4000</code>.</li>
  <li>When youâ€™re satisfied, push your changes to your own fork.</li>
  <li>Finally make a pull request from your source branch to the arfc source 
branch.</li>
</ol>

<p>If youâ€™re feeling confident, you can skip the pull request. Instead, you can 
just push changes to the website directly with the command <code class="highlighter-rouge">rake publish</code>. Only 
do this if you donâ€™t need anyone to double check your work.</p>

<h2 id="creating-a-blog-post">Creating a Blog Post</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Once you have done the set up steps, enter the source branch of the repository. <code class="highlighter-rouge">git checkout source</code></li>
  <li>Create a blog post file in <code class="highlighter-rouge">_posts</code>. Use the proper naming convention. (e.g. 
2100-12-31-century-end.md`</li>
  <li>Donâ€™t forget to git add and git commit the post <code class="highlighter-rouge">git add _posts/2100-12-31-century-end.md</code> and <code class="highlighter-rouge">git commit -am "adds a photo of Jane Doe"</code></li>
  <li>Close the file and commit your changes (<code class="highlighter-rouge">git commit -am "added Jane Doe details to people data"</code>)</li>
  <li>Check whether your changes succeeded by typing <code class="highlighter-rouge">jekyll serve</code> from the top 
level directory of the website repository. Then, open a browser to 
<code class="highlighter-rouge">localhost:4000</code>.</li>
  <li>When youâ€™re satisfied, push your changes to your own fork.</li>
  <li>Finally make a pull request from your source directory to mine.</li>
</ol>

<p>If youâ€™re feeling confident, you can skip the pull request. Instead, you can 
just push changes to the website directly with the command <code class="highlighter-rouge">rake publish</code>. Only 
do this if you donâ€™t need anyone to double check your work.</p>

<h2 id="edits-to-the-text">Edits to the text</h2>

<p>Much like both of the above options, youâ€™ll:</p>

<ul>
  <li>enter the source branch of the repository</li>
  <li>make changes to either yml or md files</li>
  <li>check your work with <code class="highlighter-rouge">jekyll serve</code></li>
  <li>and git commit, git push</li>
  <li>finally, youâ€™ll make a pull request to the arfc branch.</li>
</ul>

